    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2069303">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2069303">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2069303)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2069303">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1361261"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1405382766 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Jul 2014 00:06</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2069303">
									

<p>This notion that every single GoI is so internationally widespread and so numerous that multiple personnel are captured by ORIA on an annual basis doesn't make a whole lot of sense to me.</p>
<p>This sort of encapsulates my issues with GoIs, actually. The level of anomalous activity that would need to be going on to make this scenario plausible would be completely unable to be covered up in any meaningful way, in which case why is any of this secret, or even considered &quot;anomalous&quot;? Toymakers, hipsters, magic hillbillies, clowns, the United Nations, industrial laboratories, United States federal agents and god knows who else are running amok in the streets of Tehran (and I assume everywhere else in the world), operating on mutable principles of reality that can be discarded at will.</p>
<p>The world in which this story occurs strikes me as essentially an ongoing real-life Looney Toons short. Which, you know, more power to the people who like that sort of thing, but it's definitely not for me.</p>

							</div>

								
					
